article.headline: Rutgers 66, Iona 51
article.story: PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Ever since J.R. Inman stopped worry about scoring, he has continued to score and started to do other things. Inman had 14 points and nine rebounds to pace Rutgers to their fourth straight win, 66-51, over Iona Saturday. It was the second straight game Inman has led the Knights in scoring and rebounding, and he leads the team in both categories for the season. "What I've tried to do over these past two games is change my mind-set," said the sophomore forward, who was 9-for-10 from the foul line. "The past couple games I've just focused on rebounding and getting to the free throw line," Inman said. "Nobody likes playing with a player who forces up shots." Anthony Farmer added 13 points for Rutgers (5-5), which extended the worst start for the Gaels (0-8) in their history. Devon Clarke led Iona with nine points, while Jaron Griffin had 11 points for Rutgers and Adrian Hill had 10 points and nine rebounds before limping off early in the second half with a bruised knee. There was some concern for Hill at the time, as Hill had three knee surgeries in the past two years, but coach Fred Hill said that the forward could have returned if they needed him. "I knew the difference from when I got hurt before," Adrian Hill said. "I just banged it, it wasn't any grind or anything like that." Rutgers jumped to a 13-1 lead as Iona did not score a field goal in the game's first 5:12. The Gaels gradually battled back into it and pulled to within 29-28 with 2:25 remaining in the first half. Farmer then scored five points in a 7-0 run that gave the Knights a 36-28 halftime advantage. "That was definitely a sense of urgency right there," Farmer said. "We knew we had to step it up. We were giving them life, and that's what we didn't want to do." Rutgers kept the momentum going into the second half, as they expanded the 7-0 run to 14-2 early in the second half to open a 43-30 lead. The Gaels never got the margin under double figures from that point, as Rutgers led by as much as 17 on five separate occasions. "We didn't play extremely well but we still won," Fred Hill said. "You're definitely making progress when you don't play your best game and still win by 15 points." The Scarlet Knights have not trailed in their last two games, and the only tie was at 2-2 against Princeton. "That says that our confidence is gaining and defense is why we have it," Inman said. "Even though sometimes we struggle to score, we don't let other teams score." Iona, which shot 34 percent, has lost seven games by double figures.
